# SplitEpic Implementation-First Guidance

SplitEpic is implementation-first because it creates the machine-consumed split bundle that partitions one strategic opportunity into implementation-bearing child epics.

The sanctioned output boundary is the split bundle consumed by the split transition.

The bundle includes the split plan and `# FILE: .agents/epic-N.md` child epic sections required by the prompt contract.

Child epic files are primary contracted outputs, not invalid auxiliary artifacts.

The bundle is valid because it supplies capability partitioning, coverage proof, non-overlap evidence, sibling dependencies, split lineage input, and selected-child promotion input.

Each child epic should follow the CreateNewEpic authoring standard at the concept level: complete strategic purpose, desired capability, repository grounding, scope, non-goals, assumptions, dependencies, constraints, acceptance criteria, risks, milestone roadmap, and implementation-ready completion signals.

SplitEpic owns the capability partition.

It must prove coverage of the original opportunity, prevent overlapping ownership, define sibling dependencies, and preserve selected-child promotion semantics.

Splits are invalid when they merely divide planning phases, file areas, implementation layers, task lists, or work breakdowns.

If the proposal cannot be decomposed into coherent capability-owning child epics, output the documented `# Split Epic Blocked` response.
